poems.body:
There is a piece of damage on my old, mad bones. 
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
My muscles cannot contain it.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
In the wind found the crane, clamored its neck. 
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Clasped its cables. 
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
We were born to shovel dirt — I left my hands behind in it.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Places on my body, born with pricks. 
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
I am wicked when I crawl in it.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
It is she, a gargoyle wind from the streets around grove. 
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
From flesh she is mine, born in my breasts as wind brings the traveler home, now mad 
murderous at the ones who created her. 
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
This cannot be it.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
I have never been as mad as at my father, who will not give his son to wind.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
If I could let fear wind long like cables of the crane, imagined to be yellow, I could be a hairless 
automatic who wished herself unborn.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
A breath of tracheal wind — each day I must ration being born.
